From e89c0b23f98aae76eeff1a99c683c51bf038964c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alessandro Colace <ale.colace@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 1 May 2026 18:51:15 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] fix(v4): break circular import between classic schemas
 and iso (#5275)

`packages/zod/src/v4/classic/schemas.ts` imported `./iso.js` to forward
deprecated `ZodString.{datetime,date,time,duration}` proxies, while
`./iso.js` imported back from `./schemas.js` to extend `ZodStringFormat`.
Rollup (and other bundlers) reported this two-way cycle.

Move the `ZodISODateTime/Date/Time/Duration` class definitions into
`schemas.ts` next to their `ZodStringFormat` base, and call the
underlying `core._iso*` builders directly from the deprecated proxies.
`iso.ts` becomes a thin namespace facade that re-exports the classes
from `schemas.ts` and exposes the `z.iso.{datetime,date,time,duration}`
builder functions.

Public API is unchanged - `z.iso.datetime()`, `z.iso.ZodISODateTime`,
top-level `ZodISODateTime`, and `z.string().datetime()` all behave as
before. The cycle is gone in both directions.

Adds two regression tests:

- `packages/zod/src/v4/classic/tests/no-circular-imports.test.ts` - fast
  static-analysis check over the classic source tree (DFS on the import
  graph); fails on any future cycle.
- `packages/treeshake/tests/no-circular-imports.test.ts` - bundles three
  zod entries via rollup's programmatic API (concurrently) and asserts
  no `CIRCULAR_DEPENDENCY` warning involves zod sources. Mirrors the
  exact rollup pass that originally surfaced the issue.
